The '''Muslim Congress Party''' was a [[political party]] in [[the Gambia]]. The party was founded during the pre-independence period to represent the Muslim population in the colony of [[Banjul|Bathurst]] (now Banjul). The party was led by I. Garba-Jahumpa.<ref name="code">[http://www.codesria.org/Links/Publications/ad3_2000/edie.pdf Democracy in The Gambia by Carlene J Edie<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927164212/http://www.codesria.org/Links/Publications/ad3_2000/edie.pdf |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref> The party emerged from the Bathurst Young Muslim Society.<ref name="ppp">Hughes, Arnold. ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/484012 From Green Uprising to National Reconciliation: The People's Progressive Party in the Gambia 1959-1973]'', in Canadian Journal of African Studies / Revue Canadienne des Études Africaines, Vol. 9, No. 1. (1975), pp. 61-74.</ref>

Garba-Jahumpa won one of the three directly elected seat in the Legislative Council in [[Gambian legislative election, 1951|1951]] and [[Gambian legislative election, 1954|1954]], as the MCP candidate.<ref>Hughes, Arnold ; Perfect, Davi. ''[https://www.jstor.org/stable/723036 Trade Unionism in the Gambia]'' , in ''African Affairs'', Vol. 88, No. 353. (Oct., 1989), pp. 549-572.</ref> It contested the [[Gambian legislative election, 1960|1960 election]] in alliance with the [[People's Progressive Party (Gambia)|People's Progressive Party]] (which was based in the rural areas).<ref name="ppp"/>

Ahead of the [[Gambian legislative election, 1962|1962 election]], the MCP merged with the [[Democratic Party (Gambia)|Democratic Party]] to form the [[Democratic Congress Alliance]].<ref name="code"/>

