The '''Prague Biennale''' is an international art exhibition in [[Prague]], Czech Republic, held in alternate (odd-numbered) years. It was founded in 2003 by [[Helena Kontova]] and [[Giancarlo Politi]].<ref name=bf /> It is supported by the Czech [[Ministry of Culture (Czech Republic)|Minister of Culture]] and the City of [[Prague]]. The ''[[New York Times]]'' said of it in 2009: "Now in its fourth iteration, the biennial has a reputation for working on the cheap (the lighting is minimal to nonexistent, meaning viewings have to end by sundown) and for offering the first appearance of emerging artists from Central and Eastern Europe."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://travel.nytimes.com/2009/07/19/travel/19cultured.html?pagewanted=3|title=In Prague, Art is Everywhere but Not Always Easy...|date=19 July 2009|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=20 January 2013 | first=Evan | last=Rail}}</ref>
The Prague Biennale is a partner organisation of the [[Biennial Foundation]].<ref name=bf>{{cite web|url=http://www.biennialfoundation.org/biennials/prague-biennale/|title=Prague Biennale|publisher=Biennial Foundation|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>
==Biennales== ===1. 2003=== The first Prague Biennale had the title "Peripheries become the center" and took place from 26 June to 24 August at the [[National Gallery in Prague]]'s Veletrzni Palac.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguebiennale.org/pages/pressarea.php|title=Prague Biennale 1|publisher=Prague Biennale|accessdate=20 January 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130415145515/http://www.praguebiennale.org/pages/pressarea.php|archivedate=15 April 2013|df=}}</ref>
===2. 2005=== The second biennale took place from 26 May to 15 September at the Karlin Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://praguebiennale.org/2/|title=Prague Biennale 2|publisher=Prague Biennale|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>
===3. 2007=== The third biennale took place from 24 May to 16 September at the Karlin Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguebiennale.org/3/eng/index.html|title=Prague Biennale 3|publisher=Prague Biennale|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>
===4. 2009=== The fourth biennale took place from 14 May to 26 July at the Karlin Hall and was one of the events of the Czech [[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Presidency of the European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eu2009.cz/event/2/2841/index.html|title=Prague Biennale 4|publisher=EU2009.CZ|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>
===5. 2011=== The fifth biennale took place from 19 May to 11 September at the new venue of Microna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.praguebiennale.org/Prague_Biennale_5/Prague_Biennale_5.html|title=Prague Biennale 5|publisher=Prague Biennale|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>
===6. 2013=== The 6th Prague Biennale opened at the [[Žižkov freight railway station]] in Prague on 6 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://praguebiennale.org|title=Prague Biennale home page|accessdate=9 June 2013}}</ref>
